      <p>Underquoting is one of those topics where public perception, media coverage, and actual law in Queensland do not always line up. Vendors sometimes arrive at their first meeting with an agent already convinced that a lower price guide will attract more buyers, more competition, and therefore a higher final result. Agents occasionally oblige, using a price guide that is materially below what the vendor actually wants. The result is almost always a worse outcome than an honest price guide would have produced, and in some cases it produces real legal exposure for the agent and complaints to the regulator.</p>

      <p>This article walks through how price advertising works under Queensland law, why underquoting produces weaker results than honest pricing, how to recognise the behaviour if an agent is suggesting it, and what a seller should reasonably expect from an agent's price guide in 2027. This is a general guide, not legal advice, and specific concerns should be discussed with a Queensland-licensed solicitor or with the Office of Fair Trading.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How price advertising law works in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Queensland does not have a bespoke "underquoting act" in the way that New South Wales does (where the Property and Stock Agents Act contains explicit underquoting provisions). Instead, underquoting in Queensland is captured under the Australian Consumer Law (ACL) provisions against misleading and deceptive conduct, and under the Property Occupations Act 2014 which governs agent conduct more generally. Both frameworks apply: an agent who advertises a price that is materially below what the seller is actually prepared to accept, or below what the agent reasonably believes the property will sell for, is engaging in misleading conduct.</p>

      <p>The practical tests the regulator and courts consider are straightforward. Does the advertised price accurately reflect the agent's genuine opinion of the likely sale range? Does it accurately reflect what the seller would actually accept? Is the price range narrow enough to be useful to a buyer, or is it drawn so wide that it is essentially meaningless? If the answer to any of these is no, the advertising is likely to be misleading, and both the agent and the agency can face penalties, loss of licence, and civil claims from buyers who relied on the advertised guide.</p>

      <p>The specific forms of advertising that attract scrutiny include printed price guides in brochures, online portal listings with price fields, and verbal quotes at open homes. A "plus" notation (for example, "$1.2M+") does not provide immunity: if the reasonable expected range is $1.5M to $1.6M, advertising at "$1.2M+" is misleading because it suggests the property might sell near that number. Similarly, a wide range like "$1.2M to $1.8M" can be misleading if the agent's genuine opinion is that the property will sell in the upper half of that range.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The intuitive appeal, and why it does not work</h2>
      <p>The argument for underquoting is superficially appealing. A lower price guide attracts more buyers to the open home. More buyers at the open home creates the perception of competition. Competition drives the price up. Therefore, a lower price guide produces a higher final sale. Vendors hear this logic and agents occasionally encourage it, particularly when the agent is trying to win a listing and is worried that a realistic price guide will put off a seller who has unrealistic expectations.</p>

      <p>The evidence from actual sales data tells a different story. Properties with honest price guides consistently attract better outcomes than those with underquoted guides, for several connected reasons.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Wrong buyers turn up.</strong> If your property is genuinely a $1.5M house and the guide is $1.2M+, the open home fills with buyers whose budget is $1.2M to $1.3M. These buyers cannot afford the property. They drive the attendance numbers up but they do not drive offers up. The real $1.5M buyers, seeing a $1.2M+ guide, assume the property is either overpriced when it goes to offer stage or is not actually a $1.5M property at all, and many of them simply skip the campaign.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Competition is hollow.</strong> What underquoting produces is not genuine competition but the appearance of it. A crowd of 30 people at an open home looks exciting, but if 25 of them cannot afford the property, the actual bidding pool is 5. An honest guide at the true price point would have brought 10 genuine buyers, of whom 6 or 7 would have proceeded to offers. The honest guide produces a deeper bidding pool even though the crowd looks smaller.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Trust erosion.</strong> Once buyers realise they have been underquoted (which becomes obvious when they start seeing offers come in above the guide range), they lose trust in the agent and often in the property itself. They wonder what else is being misrepresented, and some of them walk away rather than continue in a process they feel was misleading from the start. Trust is an underappreciated factor in property sales, and it is worth more than the short-term boost from an inflated attendance figure.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Days on market blow out.</strong> Because the wrong buyers attend and the right buyers stay away, underquoted campaigns often produce no serious offers in the first two to three weeks, forcing a price guide revision or a quiet adjustment. The listing then sits on the market as agents scramble to re-engage the right audience. Days on market increase, and every extra week the property sits reduces its perceived desirability and typically the final price.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer complaints and regulator action.</strong> Underquoting is increasingly visible to Queensland's Office of Fair Trading. Buyers who feel misled, particularly those who have paid for building and pest inspections on properties they then cannot actually compete for, are more willing than they used to be to submit formal complaints. The regulator is taking those complaints seriously.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What an honest price guide actually looks like</h2>
      <p>An honest price guide in Queensland is a range that reflects the agent's genuine, evidence-based opinion of the likely sale price. It should be based on recent comparable sales, the current state of buyer demand, and any property-specific factors (presentation, position, improvements). The range should be narrow enough to be useful, typically within 10 to 15% from low to high, and it should be consistent with what the seller would actually accept.</p>

      <p>For a standard Brisbane inner-east home in 2027, an honest guide might look like "$1.45M to $1.55M" or "$1.4M plus", where the agent expects the sale to land within or very close to that stated range. If an offer comes in materially above the stated range (for example, a $1.7M offer on a $1.4M+ guide), that is a legitimate surprise and not a sign of misrepresentation. What is not legitimate is quoting $1.2M+ when the agent and vendor both know the property will not sell below $1.5M.</p>

      <p>Honest guides produce the right audience. Buyers who attend an open home with a realistic guide know the property is within their range, engage seriously with it, and come to the offer stage as genuine competition. The campaign runs faster, the final result is stronger, and the seller avoids the regulatory and reputational risk of an underquoted listing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to recognise underquoting if an agent is proposing it</h2>
      <p>Sellers occasionally find themselves in a listing presentation where an agent is suggesting a price guide that feels low compared to the agent's stated opinion of value. Several signs should prompt a closer look.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The guide is materially below the comparable sales.</strong> If recent comparable sales in your street and suburb have achieved $1.5M to $1.6M for similar properties, a guide of $1.2M+ on your home is not consistent with the market evidence. Ask the agent to walk through the comparables that justify the suggested guide. If they cannot, the guide is probably too low.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent's verbal opinion is higher than the written guide.</strong> This is a specific pattern: an agent tells the seller privately they expect the property to sell for $1.55M, then proposes to advertise it at $1.35M+ to "bring the crowds in". This is textbook underquoting and the seller should push back. The advertised guide should match the agent's genuine opinion of price.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The proposed reserve is well above the guide.</strong> If the auction reserve is set at $1.5M but the advertised guide is $1.2M+, the agent is conceding that the property will not sell at the guide price. That is the definition of misleading advertising.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent cites "generating interest" as the reason for the lower guide.</strong> This is the standard defence of underquoting, and it does not hold up. Interest generated by misrepresentation is not useful interest; it is noise. Genuine buyer interest comes from accurate pricing combined with strong marketing and presentation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Auctions and "no price" campaigns</h2>
      <p>Queensland law does allow a seller to run an auction campaign without advertising a price at all. Auction campaigns frequently use "auction" or "contact agent" in place of a price range, on the basis that the market will set the price on the day. This is legitimate and not a form of underquoting, provided the agent does not supplement it with verbal or written guides that are materially below the genuine reserve.</p>

      <p>The trap in no-price auction campaigns is what the agent says at the open home. Buyers will always ask "what are you expecting?" or "where are you thinking this will land?" A buyer who is told "we're hoping for around $1.3M" when the reserve is $1.55M has been given misleading information, regardless of what the advertised materials say. The same rules apply verbally as they do in print: the agent's stated opinion should match the seller's actual expectations.</p>

      <p>Well-run auction campaigns in Queensland tend to give buyers clear guidance on the likely price range in private conversation, even when public materials do not include a price. This is legal, useful to buyers, and produces better engagement from genuine bidders. What it is not is a licence to underquote.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Offers over and range quoting</h2>
      <p>The most common price guide formats in Queensland are "offers over $X", "offers above $X", "$X+", and price ranges such as "$X to $Y". All of these can be used honestly, and all of them can be misused.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Offers over $X.</strong> The figure should represent the lower end of the agent's expected price range. "Offers over $1.4M" is appropriate when the agent genuinely believes the property will sell between $1.4M and (say) $1.55M. "Offers over $1.2M" when the expectation is $1.5M is underquoting.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Price ranges ($X to $Y).</strong> The range should cover the agent's actual opinion of the likely sale price, and it should be reasonably narrow. A 30% range (for example, $1.2M to $1.6M) is usually too wide to be meaningful and will often be treated as misleading. A 10 to 15% range is standard.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Contact agent.</strong> This format is legitimate for auction or off-market campaigns. It is not a licence to quote materially different numbers to different buyers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should insist on</h2>
      <p>If you are listing a property, the question to ask your agent is straightforward: "What price guide will you use, and can you walk me through the comparable sales that justify it?" The agent should be able to show you three to five recent sales of comparable properties (same suburb, similar size and condition, sold within the last 3 to 6 months) that support the proposed guide. If the comparables show $1.5M and the agent is proposing a $1.2M guide, ask why. There may be a legitimate answer (for example, a soft local market or a property-specific issue that justifies a lower range), but the answer should be clear and evidence-based.</p>

      <p>It is also reasonable to ask your agent what price you would realistically accept, and then confirm that the advertised guide is consistent with that figure. If you would not accept anything below $1.45M, the advertised guide should reflect that reality. A guide significantly below your walk-away price is, by definition, misleading to buyers and damaging to your campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The data-led case for honest pricing</h2>
      <p>Real estate data across Queensland consistently shows that accurately priced listings sell faster and, on average, for a higher net result than underquoted listings. The mechanics are clear: honest pricing attracts qualified buyers, qualified buyers compete seriously, and serious competition produces strong prices. Underquoted listings, by contrast, typically produce the appearance of competition without the substance, and they often end up selling at or near the underquoted range because the right buyers were never in the room.</p>

      <p>For Brisbane's inner east in 2027, the data is especially clear in family home price brackets ($1.2M to $2.5M), where buyers are discerning, comparable sales information is transparent, and the market has a long memory for campaigns that felt misleading. A reputation for honest pricing is a genuine asset for both agent and seller, and honest pricing is almost always the approach that produces the best actual outcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>Underquoting in Queensland is a strategy that feels clever but rarely works. It exposes agents to regulatory action, erodes buyer trust, attracts the wrong audience, and consistently produces weaker final prices than honest pricing. If an agent is proposing a price guide that feels low relative to your suburb's comparable sales or your own walk-away price, ask for the evidence. If the evidence is not there, insist on a more honest guide. Your campaign will be shorter, your buyer pool will be better qualified, and your final result will, in almost every case, be better. Good agents know this and price accordingly; the minority who do not are a liability to both the seller and the wider industry.</p>

